      {
         "id": "SECTION_prerequisites",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><span id=\"htAgeMsg\"></span></p><p><span id=\"htAmericaAbyaYalaMsg\"></span> (<htcite0>).</p><p style=\"font-style: italic;\" id=\"htChinaZhongguo\"></p><p style=\"font-style: italic;\" id=\"htJapanNipponNihonKoku\"></p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "160fb48c-1711-491e-a1aa-e1257e7889af",
                     "text": "Porto-Gonçalves, Carlos Walter",
                     "page": "pp. 39-43",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2011",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nIn this, we will continue learning about different ways of representing the numbers we use to count. This time, we will get to know the Soroban (算盤), developed in Japan (Nippon koku ou Nihon koku, 日本国).\n\nTo better understand it, we recommend studying the previous texts (<htcite0>; <htcite1>) before proceeding.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9618a83e-f232-49db-84f6-fc3455a3f1d1",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Drawing to Count",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "648fb7b4-ba73-452e-980b-6d68d57d16b9",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Our actual number",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn the previous texts, we learned that Indigenous peoples of the Americas (*Abya Yala*) possibly used their own bodies to create different ways of counting.\n\nIn another text from History Tracers, we studied that some Indigenous peoples of the Americas (*Abya Yala*) share common ancestors with some Japanese people, despite having lived apart for a long period of time (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9ba61aa2-28ec-4667-b7af-5a4076f865dd",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Jōmon Period (縄文)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: There as Here</b><br /><br />Do you think that the Japanese could also have created instruments to represent counting, such as the yupana (<htcite0>; <htcite1>)?<br /><br />Would these conclusions have influenced each other, or were they discovered independently?</div></div></center>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9ba61aa2-28ec-4667-b7af-5a4076f865dd",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Jōmon Period (縄文)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_origin",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Origin\n\nRegarding the origin of the tool we will study, the Soroban (算盤) (**Figura 1**) (<htcite0>), there is no consensus on which people were the first to develop a calculation tool, also popularly known as the abacus. It may have emerged in different places independently or originated in a single place, spreading through trade (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8ab7ebef-41db-4f2b-a3e3-3530e7ff29d3",
                     "text": "Shigetoshi Oyabu",
                     "page": "fl. 14",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1842",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "88d236e3-7db4-4085-848e-0346101e6e51",
                     "text": "Samoly, K.",
                     "page": "pp. 59 - 61",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2012",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgTohoku\" src=\"\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgTohoku', '0%')\" /><b>Figura 1</b>: Shigetoshi Oyabu. Preserved by the Tohoku University Main Library (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8ab7ebef-41db-4f2b-a3e3-3530e7ff29d3",
                     "text": "Shigetoshi Oyabu",
                     "page": "fl. 14",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1842",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Despite the different possible origins, there is consensus that the Soroban (算盤) arrived in Japan (Nippon koku or Nihon koku, 日本国) from China (Zhongguo, 中國), with the Chinese model (suanpan, 算盤) being somewhat different (<htcite0>).\n\nRegarding the possible connection between how the Incas possibly used the yupana (<htcite1>) and the use of the Soroban (算盤), there is no evidence of contact between these peoples; thus, it is assumed that the development of these tools occurred independently.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "88d236e3-7db4-4085-848e-0346101e6e51",
                     "text": "Samoly, K.",
                     "page": "pp. 60 - 61",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2012",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_writting",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Remembering the Indigenous Peoples\n\nThe best way to learn something new is based on what we have seen before. Thus, let us recall the indigenous models we have already studied.\n\n#### The Yupana\n\nOne of the first numerical representation models we learned about was the yupana. To remember it, use the arrows in Table 1 to recall how we filled it according to the **Table 1** to recall how we filled it according to the *\"Yupana Inka Tawa Pukllay\"* method and the relationship between numbers and our hand (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Yupana</i></th><th>Left hand</th><th>Right hand</th><th>Arrows</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_center\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c1_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_up\"></span><span class=\"dot five_dot_c2_bottom\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\"><span class=\"dot three_dot_bottom\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_up\"></span><span class=\"dot three_dot_center\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc3f1\"><span class=\"dot two_dot_bottom\"></span> <span class=\"dot two_dot_up\"></span></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"><span class=\"dot dot_center\"></span></td><td id=\"tc5f1\"><img id=\"leftHandImg\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('leftHandImg', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/0Left_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc6f1\"><img id=\"rightHandImg\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('rightHandImg', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/0Right_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc7f1\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp0\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\"style=\"font-size:4em;color:#00f;\" id=\"traineeDown0\"></td></tr></table>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Representation of one line of the <i>Yupana</i> according to Poma de Ayala (<htcite0> ; <htcite1>). CSS inspired by W3schools code (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('48dd9187-7ecc-4f54-a387-d9ecc2497de3'); return false;\">W3school</span></a>)</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "pp. 355",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1",
                     "text": "Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman",
                     "page": "pp. 361 - 362",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1615",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "From the yupana (**Table 1**), we can observe that we represent our fingers in stages. For the first three fingers, we have one quadrant for each. For the fourth finger, we represent it with two quadrants (the quadrant with 1 and the quadrant with 3). Next, we have an isolated quadrant for when we have all five fingers raised; for the remaining numbers, we keep all five digits always selected and add values in the other quadrants until we reach nine raised fingers (<htcite0>).\n\n#### Mesoamerica\n\nFrom the indigenous peoples of Mesoamerica, we understand that numbers 1 through 4 are represented as circles, which could symbolize our fingertips, while a bar represents the number 5. For numbers 6 through 9, there is a combination of the previous ones. See **Table 2** to remember:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a62b520a-f443-4d83-ab51-b99c9a46dab8",
                     "text": "Prem, Dhavit",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<table class=\"tawapukllay\" id=\"tblHandsCounting\"><tr><th>Left hand</th><th>Right hand</th><th>Indigenous count</th><th>Our numbers</th></tr> <tr id=\"tr0\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr1\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr2\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr3\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr4\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr5\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr6\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr7\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr8\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr9\"></tr> <tr id=\"tr10\"></tr>  </table>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 2</b>: Mesoamerican numeration associated with our hands.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Alterations</b><br /><br />Both the indigenous peoples of the Andes and those of Mesoamerica, in the Americas (<i>Abya Yala</i>) used circles to represent numbers. However, they combined these symbols in different ways.<br /><br />Would it be possible to replace the circles we are seeing with beans?<br /><br />Beyond this change, can you go further and imagine a new way to represent numbers between 0 and 9?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
